","about 1250":"about 1250","about 1292":"about 1292","about 1290":"about 1290","1340":"1340","1294":"1294","1250":"1250","26 November 1294":"26 November 1294","1292":"1292","unknown":"before 1290","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","November 1316":"November 1316","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","1225":"1225","1257":"1257","1235":"1235","1378":"1378","11 Nov 1316":"11 November 1316","1255":"1255","1353":"1353","about 1257":"about 1257","1317":"1317","Stokesay, Shropshire, England":"Stokesay, Shropshire, England","Ludlow, Shropshire, England":"Ludlow, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ludlowe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: habitational name from a place in Shropshire, so named from the Old English river name <i>Hlūde</i> (from <i>hlūd</i> ‘loud, roaring’) referring to the Teme river + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill’. This name was taken Ireland in the 13th and 17th centuries. See also   Laidlaw  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Laidlaw","meanings":["Scottish: Border surname found mainly around Selkirk and the vales of Ettrick and Yarrow; a Scottish development of   Ludlow  ."]},{"name":"Ledlow","meanings":["English, Irish, or Scottish: variant of   Ludlow   or   Laidlaw  ."]},{"name":"Ludlam","meanings":["English: possibly from a misreading of <i>w</i> as <i>m</i> in <i>Ludelawe</i>, a recorded medieval spelling of the placename <i>Ludlow</i> in Shropshire. Compare   Ludlow  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Ludlowe was born about 1250, in Ludlow, Shropshire, England, his father, Sir Lawrence de Ludlow Lord of Stokesey, was 17 and his mother, Agnes Ludlow, was 27. He had at least 3 sons with Matilda Maud Hodnet. He died on 11 November 1316, in Stokesay, Shropshire, England, at the age of 67, and was buried in Stokesay, Shropshire, England."},"et":{"about 1250–11 Nov 1316":"umbes 1250–11. november 1316","1250–1316":"1250–1316","1255–1347":"1255–1347","1290–1353":"1290–1353","1290–1340":"1290–1340","1292–1378":"1292–1378","1235–1294":"1235–1294","1225–1257":"1225–1257","about 1250":"umbes 1250","about 1292":"umbes 1292","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1340":"1340","1294":"1294","1250":"1250","26 No